The commit adds useful ZIP/link/automation plumbing, but the new URL automation path is too trusting for a localhost 
app with filesystem APIs. I found two automation issues that can write or translate the wrong package, plus a link URL 
validation bypass and a direction-validation bug in the dev translate entry point.

- [P0] URL automation is CSRFable through top-level navigation - app.js:337-390  
  Any website can navigate the browser to `http://127.0.0.1:<port>/?package=...&autoTranslate=1&autoSave=1`; once 
loaded, the app treats the query string as user intent and calls local filesystem APIs from same origin. Require an 
explicit server-issued automation token or local opt-in flag, and do not approve/load arbitrary `package` paths from 
URL parameters without confirmation.

- [P1] Automation continues after package load failure - app.js:371-390  
  `runAutomation()` awaits `loadFolderFromServer(pkg)` but the callee returns normally for “no supported files” and 
catches load errors, so automation can continue against a previously auto-loaded package. Make `loadFolderFromServer` 
return success/throw on failure, then abort translate/save unless the requested package actually loaded.

- [P1] Editing an existing link bypasses URL safety validation - app.js:8205-8219  
  New link annotations go through `createAnnotation()` and `isSafeUrl()`, but updating an exact-range existing link 
assigns `ex.url = url` without validation. Validate before updating and reject unsafe URLs there too; also consider 
normalizing loaded/saved link annotations so unsafe legacy values cannot persist.

- [P2] Invalid automation direction silently uses stale config - dev_translate.js:620-637  
  `__devTranslateRun({ direction })` calls `applyQuickDirection`, but if the direction is unsupported it still runs 
translation with whatever config was previously stored. Return an error and abort when a non-empty direction is 
invalid, especially because URL automation can combine this with `autoSave=1`.
